PPVI identification and segmentation.text:
We identified chronic PPVI using the following MRI criteria 19,20 (Fig. 1A): (1) focal periventricular white matter lesions;
(2) hypointense signals on both T1WI and FLAIR images; (3) black dots sign within lesions on SWI images; (4) gray matter sparing. The black dots sign on SWI images is important for differentiating PPVI from lacunes (Fig. 1B). Notably, PPVI should be distinguished from enlarged perivascular spaces which were round, oval, or linear,  3 mm in their maximum diameter, with smooth delineated contours surrounding the perforating arteries 21. To increase the visibility of the black dots sign within lesions and reduce the effects of noise and artifacts, we processed the SWI images using a new approach called CLEAR-SWI, which has the advantage of eliminating the phase warp artifacts. This method could improve image homogeneity and contrast-to-noise ratio compared with standard SWI methods 22. All images were reviewed by two experienced radiologists (X.F.Y. and X.D.) blind to clinical information. Discrepancies were resolved by discussion.
We segmented PPVI based on T1WI images. Skullstripped T1WI images were segmented into three classes using FMRIBs Automated Segmentation Tool: white matter, gray matter, and cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). As the PPVI had the same signal as CSF, it appeared on the image of partial volume estimates for CSF (PVE-CSF). Thus, we obtained the PPVI mask from the PVE-CSF images by applying an intensity threshold and a region-growth method. Lacunes and perivascular spaces were carefully avoided and manually removed if they were mis-included. Finally, the PPVI volume was calculated. To avoid the influence of head size, we also calculated the intracranial volume (ICV) from the T1WI image using FreeSurfer and corrected the PPVI volume using ICV.
